  "expected_detection": {
    "should_alert_on": "attack_sequence",
    "should_not_alert_on": "benign_similar",
    "key_fields": [
      "process.name",
      "process.command_line",
      "process.parent.name",
      "process.parent.executable",
      "process.executable",
      "user.name"
    ],
    "notes": "Detection signal: flag rapid sequential spawning of systeminfo, wmic, ipconfig, hostname, whoami, and net config within a short time window (< 5s) from a common non-standard parent process. The parent executable path in AppData\\Local\\Temp is a strong high-confidence indicator — legitimate admin tools are rarely parented from Temp. Correlate process.parent.executable matching *\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\* with child process.name in [cmd.exe, wmic.exe, systeminfo.exe, ipconfig.exe, net.exe] using a sequence or aggregation rule. Benign cases are distinguished by: trusted/signed parents (devenv.exe, MsMpEng.exe), SYSTEM context, single-command (non-chained) invocations, and output redirection to user-visible locations."
  },
